SIMPLE: replication
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Replication
<hw>Rep`li*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(-k?"sh?n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>replicatio</ets>. See <er>Reply</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An
answer; a reply.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Withouten any <qex>repplicacioun</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law Pleadings)</fld> <def>The reply of the
plaintiff, in matters of fact, to the defendant's plea.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Return or repercussion, as of sound; echo.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To hear the <qex>replication</qex> of your sounds.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A repetition; a copy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Biochem.)</fld> <def>The copying, by enzymes, of a
cell's genome, i.e. the DNA or RNA comprising its genetic material, so
as to form an identical genome. This is an essential step in the
division of one cell into two. This differs from
<contr>transcription</contr>, which is the copying of only part of the
genetic information of a cell's genome into RNA, as in the processes of
biosynthesis of messenger RNA or ribosomal RNA.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Answer; response; reply; rejoinder.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Replier</ent>⟦br⟧
